–1386","1296–1348":"1296–1348","1295–1350":"1295–1350","1340":"1340","1296":"1296","abt 1350":"circa 1350","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1337":"1337","1348":"1348","1326":"1326","1312":"1312","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","about 1348":"circa 1348","1375":"1375","1386":"1386","1408":"1408","1406":"1406","1339":"1339","1328":"1328","Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England","Carnforth, Lancashire, England":"Carnforth, Lancashire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1320–1375":"1320–1375","1326–Male":"1326–Deceased","1328–1408":"1328–1408","1340–1406":"1340–1406","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1326–1386":"1326–1386","1296–1348":"1296–1348","1295–1350":"1295–1350","1340":"1340","1296":"1296","abt 1350":"about 1350","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1337":"1337","1348":"1348","1326":"1326","1312":"1312","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","about 1348":"about 1348","1375":"1375","1386":"1386","1408":"1408","1406":"1406","1339":"1339","1328":"1328","Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England","Carnforth, Lancashire, England":"Carnforth, Lancashire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Washington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Washington in Durham, possibly also from Washington in Sussex. The Durham placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Hwassa</i>, <i>Hwæssa</i> + the Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. In North America, this surname is by far most common among African Americans (see 2 below).","African American: from the personal name <i>Washington</i> (or <i>George Washington</i>), adopted in honor of George Washington, the 1st president of the US; or adoption of the surname in 1 above, in most cases probably for the same reason.","History: George Washington (1732–99), 1st president of the US (1789–97), was born at Bridges Creek, VA. His great-grandfather had emigrated from Dillicar in Westmorland in 1658. George Washington was a slaveowner, but he became troubled with the institution of slavery. Shortly before his death he decided that his slaves have to be freed after the death of his wife. — With the passage of time, the surname Washington has come to be borne by more African Americans (around 90% of all bearers) than English-Americans. A prominent example was the educator Booker T. Washington (1856–1915), born a slave in VA, who adopted his surname from his stepfather, Washington Ferguson."],"variants":[{"name":"President","meanings":["African American: from the English vocabulary word <i>president</i>, probably adopted as a surname in honor of one of the early presidents of the US (compare   Washington   and   Jefferson  ) or simply because of the importance of the presidential function."]},{"name":"Washinton","meanings":["Altered form of English   Washington  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":8,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":17,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Washington III was born in 1320, in Carnforth, Lancashire, England, his father, Robert Washington, was 24 and his mother, Agnes le Gentyl, was 26. He married Margery Hawkin in 1339, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1375, in Carnforth, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1320–1375":"1320–1375","1326–Male":"1326–Surnud","1328–1408":"1328–1408","1340–1406":"1340–1406","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1326–1386":"1326–1386","1296–1348":"1296–1348","1295–1350":"1295–1350","1340":"1340","1296":"1296","abt 1350":"umbes 1350","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1337":"1337","1348":"1348","1326":"1326","1312":"1312","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","about 1348":"umbes 1348","1375